<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>ADMISSION CONTROLLER BYPASS</title>

  <critical>Admission controllers are Kubernetes' gatekeepers, validating and mutating resources before persistence. Bypassing OPA Gatekeeper, Kyverno, or custom webhooks allows deployment of malicious or non-compliant resources. Webhook failures, namespace exemptions, and resource type gaps create bypass opportunities.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Webhook failure modes
    - Namespace and resource exemptions
    - OPA Gatekeeper bypass
    - Kyverno policy bypass
    - Timing and race conditions
    - API group and version gaps
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. ADMISSION CONTROLLER ENUMERATION
       {% raw %}
       # List admission webhooks
       kubectl get validatingwebhookconfigurations
       kubectl get mutatingwebhookconfigurations

       # Check webhook configuration
       kubectl get validatingwebhookconfigurations -o yaml

       # Key fields to check:
       # - namespaceSelector: Which namespaces are affected
       # - objectSelector: Which objects are affected
       # - rules: What operations and resources
       # - failurePolicy: Fail or Ignore on error

       # Check for OPA Gatekeeper
       kubectl get constrainttemplates
       kubectl get constraints
       {% endraw %}

    2. FAILURE POLICY EXPLOITATION
       {% raw %}
       # Webhooks have failurePolicy: Fail | Ignore

       # If failurePolicy: Ignore
       # Make webhook unavailable, bypass all checks

       # Check failure policy
       kubectl get validatingwebhookconfigurations -o json | jq '.items[].webhooks[].failurePolicy'

       # Webhook unavailability:
       # - Delete webhook service
       # - DoS webhook endpoint
       # - DNS manipulation
       # - TLS certificate issues

       # Timing attack
       # Deploy during webhook maintenance window
       {% endraw %}

    3. NAMESPACE EXEMPTION BYPASS
       {% raw %}
       # Check namespace selectors

       # Common exemptions
       kubectl get validatingwebhookconfigurations -o json | jq '.items[].webhooks[].namespaceSelector'

       # Often exempt:
       # - kube-system
       # - kube-public
       # - namespaces with specific label

       # Create or use exempt namespace
       kubectl label namespace target control-plane=true  # If this exempts

       # Deploy in exempt namespace
       kubectl apply -f malicious.yaml -n kube-system

       # Check if your namespace is exempt
       kubectl auth can-i create pods -n kube-system
       {% endraw %}

    4. RESOURCE TYPE GAPS
       {% raw %}
       # Webhooks may not cover all resource types

       # Check covered resources
       kubectl get validatingwebhookconfigurations -o json | jq '.items[].webhooks[].rules[].resources'

       # Common gaps:
       # - Pods covered, but not Deployments
       # - Deployments covered, but not CronJobs
       # - Core resources covered, but not CRDs

       # Use alternative resource type
       # Instead of Pod, use:
       # - Job
       # - CronJob
       # - DaemonSet
       # - Deployment with replicas: 0 (then scale up)
       {% endraw %}

    5. OPA GATEKEEPER BYPASS
       {% raw %}
       # Enumerate Gatekeeper constraints
       kubectl get constraints

       # Check constraint template
       kubectl get constrainttemplate <name> -o yaml

       # Common bypass techniques:

       # 1. Use exempted namespace
       kubectl get constraints <name> -o json | jq '.spec.match.excludedNamespaces'

       # 2. Use exempted user/group
       kubectl get constraints <name> -o json | jq '.spec.match.scope'

       # 3. Parameter bypass
       # Constraint checks spec.containers
       # Use spec.initContainers instead

       # 4. Rego logic flaws
       # Test edge cases in constraint rules
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <version_and_group_bypass>
      {% raw %}
      # Webhooks may not cover all API versions

      # Check API version coverage
      kubectl get validatingwebhookconfigurations -o json | jq '.items[].webhooks[].rules[] | {apiGroups, apiVersions}'

      # If webhook covers apps/v1 but not apps/v1beta1
      apiVersion: apps/v1beta1  # May bypass

      # Check available API versions
      kubectl api-versions

      # Use alternative API group
      # batch/v1 vs batch/v1beta1
      {% endraw %}
    </version_and_group_bypass>

    <subresource_bypass>
      {% raw %}
      # Webhooks may not cover subresources

      # Common subresources:
      # - pods/exec
      # - pods/attach
      # - pods/portforward
      # - deployments/scale

      # If webhook covers pods but not pods/exec
      kubectl exec -it pod-name -- /bin/sh  # May bypass

      # Check subresource coverage
      kubectl get validatingwebhookconfigurations -o json | jq '.items[].webhooks[].rules[].scope'
      {% endraw %}
    </subresource_bypass>

    <reinvocation_policy>
      {% raw %}
      # Mutating webhooks can modify resources

      # If reinvocationPolicy: Never
      # Mutations by one webhook not rechecked by others

      # Attack:
      # 1. Webhook A adds container
      # 2. Webhook B validates original (pre-mutation)
      # 3. Malicious container from A not validated

      # Check reinvocation policy
      kubectl get mutatingwebhookconfigurations -o json | jq '.items[].webhooks[].reinvocationPolicy'
      {% endraw %}
    </reinvocation_policy>

    <kyverno_bypass>
      {% raw %}
      # Kyverno policy engine bypass

      # List Kyverno policies
      kubectl get clusterpolicies
      kubectl get policies -A

      # Check policy rules
      kubectl get clusterpolicy <name> -o yaml

      # Common bypasses:

      # 1. Background mode only
      # Policy validates but doesn't block
      kubectl get clusterpolicy <name> -o json | jq '.spec.validationFailureAction'
      # "audit" = log only, "enforce" = block

      # 2. Exclude resources
      kubectl get clusterpolicy <name> -o json | jq '.spec.rules[].exclude'

      # 3. Rule matching gaps
      # Policy checks Deployment but not Pod directly
      {% endraw %}
    </kyverno_bypass>

    <timing_race_conditions>
      {% raw %}
      # Race conditions in admission control

      # 1. Rapid deployment
      # Deploy many pods quickly
      # Some may slip through rate-limited webhook

      # 2. Webhook restart window
      # During webhook pod restart
      # failurePolicy: Ignore allows bypass

      # 3. Concurrent modifications
      # Create resource, immediately modify
      # Modification may bypass validation

      # 4. Cluster upgrade window
      # During Kubernetes upgrade
      # Webhooks may be temporarily unavailable
      {% endraw %}
    </timing_race_conditions>

    <sidecar_injection_bypass>
      {% raw %}
      # Mutating webhooks inject sidecars

      # If sidecar injection webhook bypassed
      # Pod runs without security sidecar

      # Bypass sidecar injection:
      # 1. Exempt namespace label
      # 2. Pod annotation: sidecar.istio.io/inject: "false"
      # 3. Host network pods (sometimes exempt)

      # Check injection rules
      kubectl get mutatingwebhookconfigurations istio-sidecar-injector -o yaml
      {% endraw %}
    </sidecar_injection_bypass>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Monitor webhook configuration changes
    - Alert on webhook unavailability
    - Track resources in exempt namespaces
    - Log admission decisions and bypasses
    - Monitor for policy audit violations
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Identify exempt namespaces
    - Exploit failure policy misconfigurations
    - Deploy restricted resource via alternative type
    - Bypass OPA/Kyverno policies
    - Document all policy gaps
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - failurePolicy: Ignore is the most dangerous misconfiguration
    - kube-system is almost always exempt from policies
    - CronJobs and DaemonSets often bypass Pod-focused policies
    - Mutating webhooks run before validating - mutation gaps persist
    - Dry-run mode (--dry-run=server) reveals validation without applying
    - kubectl auth can-i --list shows your actual permissions
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Admission controllers are only as comprehensive as their configuration. Every namespace exemption, every uncovered resource type, every API version gap is a potential bypass. Test exhaustively - use alternative resource types, different namespaces, various API versions. The security boundary isn't what policies say they cover, it's what they actually enforce.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
